post_text: In order to help inform our community about Covid-19 in the district, we have created a new "Data Dashboard" that will be updated at the end of each week. This includes Covid test positivity rates in the counties, along with district student/staff new confirmed positive cases during the week, as well as those newly quarantining due to close exposure. While we cannot share private/individual health information or list our data in a way that could allow someone to easily identify impacted individuals, we want to remain transparent as we progress through the school year and keep our community informed. Again, this will be updated at the end of each week and can be found on the school website under the "About Us" dropdown - Return to Learn / Covid-19 https://bcluw-ia.schoolloop.com/pf4/cms2/view_page?d=x&group_id=1528960711742&vdid=i22jvf2ljc4336j

BCLUW Lunch Ladies
July 10 at 1:02 PM ·

Hello all! Substitute teachers wanted! The AEA has created an additional (online) course in August for anyone interested in becoming authorized as a substitute teacher.

According to the AEA:

Substitute Authorization Course #3405
Section #284165
Dates: August 17-21
Time: Daily 9-12:00 via zoom
Cost: $130 ($100 for course and $30 textbook fee, textbook will be mailed to participants prior to start date). After the course, participants will need to apply for licensure through the BOEE at a cost of $160.
To register: https://aealearning.truenorthlogic.com/ you must log in or create a free account, enter course # in search box and follow directions to register.

For more information, you can contact Heather Staebell at Central Rivers AEA- hstaebell@centralriversaea.org

More information on the program and eligibility for obtaining licensure as a substitute teacher can be found in the flyer-

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1F1eqTBHM-vjND5lCUMgnrAJc3fL7bcvy/view?usp=sharing

shared_text:
BCLUW Elementary School
June 13 at 6:54 AM ·

Remember to order your Team Rylee shirt! (order form attached) Rylee is a sweet 10 year old with muscular dystrophy and cerebral palsy along with other special needs. She is being raised by her grandma & grandpa. Rylee is currently in Ia City hospital ICU fighting for her life. She has gone through a few different surgeries to repair blockages and a twisted intestine. They have done separate surgeries so her little body could withstand the stress. She has been on a ventilator since being transferred from Marshalltown ER and still remains on it to let her badly infected lungs heal.
T-shirts orders can be mailed or dropped off at the superintendent district office (attention Mr. Parker or Pam), or at Hutch Screenprinting during normal business hours. $5 for each shirt sold will go to benefit the family. Please let Pam or Mr. Parker know if you have any questions. When orders are filled we will contact people to arrange for pick-up times.
Order forms will also be located at Hutch Screenprinting and the Gingersnap.
Thank you for your support of Rylee during this difficult time!!

All High School students need to return laptops, chargers, bags for seniors, textbooks, college textbooks and hot spots. If you need to clean out your gym locker please let us know when you arrive, all others will stay in car. Seniors will pick up cap and gowns and take pictures.

Please remember to practice social distancing and follow the directions of the staff. We look forward to seeing everyone!

shared_text:
BCLUW Drama Department
May 20 at 9:30 PM ·

The stage is dark and will remain that way for the BCLUW Drama performance of “And Then There Were None.” The difficult decision to cancel our show has been made, and we thank you for your support during the uncertainty of the past two months.

We know that live theater has the power to connect us all in truly incredible ways. On the other side of these challenging times, BCLUW Drama will be there for us to share together in laughter, tears, and inspiration. After all, we have more stories to tell!

Until the time comes when we can once again welcome you into our seats and open the curtain, we hope you feel peace knowing that when it is safe to do so, our auditorium will be waiting for you.

post_text:
Graduation (and Prom) Update: While more details were communicated with BCLUW seniors and senior parents via email, we also wanted to share that we are hopeful to be able to hold a graduation ceremony this summer.
=========================================
Our ability to hold an in-person graduation ceremony for the class of 2020 will be dependent upon allowable gathering size, location, and social distancing regulations over the next several weeks. If we are able to hold a ceremony, we may also be limited on the number of attendees. At this time, we are planning a date in late June, with backup dates in July, to be held during the evening at the football field. Our first date for a graduation ceremony is Sunday evening, June 28. If we are not able to hold graduation at that time, our back-up dates are Friday evening, July 17, followed by (in the event of rain/poor weather that day), Sunday, July 19.

We are joining with other schools in the state, along with the IHSADA, in #LightupIowa tonight. We will be lighting up our stadium in support of students and communities for 25 minutes; one minute for every day we have missed school in April. Tonight we will be recognizing our Senior spring activity participants during the light up via a live stream.

post_text:
Resources for any that may need it from the Comet Closet. Be well Comets!!

I would like to remind people that the Comet Closet food pantry is stocked and ready to provide assistance to families in need. We would rather people use us as a resource than try to decide between buying groceries/necessities and paying bills. If you know someone in need or if you need help, please contact the Comet Closet. We are open by appointment only at this time but can usually find someone to meet up with the family within 24 hours.

If you have any questions or need assistance please contact Krista Ralston @ 641-485-6743.

Another update on "grab & go" meal availability during the school closure- based on new guidelines that were just released, students no longer need to be present to collect meals; a parent/guardian/caregiver can pick them up for the students/children. Our staff are working hard to make meals available for as many students as possible, so we encourage families to take advantage of this opportunity! (must be signed up in advance using "meal availability" forms found at https://sites.google.com/bcluw.org/bcluwclosure/home )

New locations and meal distribution time for "grab and go" meals starting Monday, March 30.

Conrad (near Elementary entrance) 11:00 - 11:30
Beaman (near library entrance) 11:45 - 12:05
Whitten (near the park) 11:00 - 11:20
Union (near Middle School main entrance) 11:35 - 12:00
Liscomb (near City Hall) 12:15 - 12:35

post_text: While we generally keep this page specific to school-related posts, BCLUW wants to take an opportunity to ask our community to continue to support our local businesses during this time. BCLUW Middle School
February 21 at 8:42 PM ·

We received some great news in our efforts to offer more STEM curriculum.

Congratulations BCLUW!
Danielle Fortsch and Mekayla Reints have completed STEM Innovator® Teacher Certification, meaning your teachers now have the skills to infuse innovation and the entrepreneurial mindset into their classroom. STEM Innovator® engages students in solving authentic, community-driven, real-world problems by working in multidisciplinary teams. STEM Innovator® students learn to identify a problem of interest, verify and validate the problem through customer discovery, and establish and implement a solution. Along the way, students explore multiple careers and gain the skills to be college and career ready.

post_text:
Hey everybody! I'm Payton Pekarek. I'm a Senior at BCLUW and I'm an active member of the BCLUW Honor Society. I'm doing my Senior Leadership project on February 24th from 6:00 p.m. to 8:00 p.m. in the BCLUW high school commons. We will be making origami cranes for Alicia Holden. She's a former BCLUW student and is battling brain cancer so if this sounds interesting to you please mark it on your calendar and let me know if you're for sure coming so I can have a count. This idea came from an Iowa high school student who started an organization to make origami cranes for her friend who was battling cancer. Please pass this on to any friends or family you think might be interested! The person who started the origami crane mission will be in attendance to help us out, so don't worry if you've never done origami! It'll be lots of fun and for a good cause. Please consider coming! This is a free event and all you need to bring is yourself!

For more information about the paper crane mission, please visithttps://origamioptimism.weebly.com/

Thanks,
Payton Pekarek

post_text:
Are you wanting to attend this weekend's production of Beauty and the Beast? If so, we encourage you to reserve your seats now for either Saturday performance (2:00 or 7:30 p.m.) . There will also be a free-will donation meal available between these performances. Make it a date night!

Very few seats remain for Friday and Sunday - if you are wishing to attend one of these performances, you may be placed on a waiting list.

Thank you for your support of BCLUW Drama!

Ticket reservations can be made until 3:30 p.m. on Friday by calling 641-366-2810 x3032 or emailing jwillett@bcluw.org. Reservations are made on a first come first served basis.

If cancellations are made to existing reservations, those on the waiting list will be contacted prior to the tickets going to will call.

At 3:30pm on Friday, all available tickets will be at will call prior to the performances. We will update the ticket availability on Friday afternoon as well.

BCLUW Middle School
November 3, 2019 at 6:53 PM ·

Hello, this is Morgan Bergman with BCLUW Middle School. For the past 19 years, we have had a Veterans Day Program to honor our Veterans. We distribute flags to veterans, read poems written by 7th and 8th graders, and sing songs to thank the veterans. For our twentieth year, we are inviting a Grammy Winning musician, Dr.Monte Selby, to write music for the Veterans Day Program. Dr. Selby specializes in education, was a professor, teacher, and principal. Our 7th and 8th-grade band will also be playing the National Anthem and all the military branch songs.

We would like you to come and honor our veterans on November 11, 2019, at 2:00 for the twentieth year celebration.

Thank you- Morgan Bergman, BCLUW 7th grade

post_text:
We are excited to announce that BCLUW was selected today as a recipient of a state grant for STEM BEST (Businesses Engaging Students and Teachers).

The STEM Best Program supports school-business partnerships that allow teachers and industry professionals to work side-by-side on curriculum and projects that give students actual workplace experience and an understanding of the opportunities and required skills for careers in STEM fields.

We also want to both congratulate and thank Mrs. Roberta Vanderah for taking the lead role in the grant application.

We'll have more information to share later, but you can find today's state press release at - https://iowastem.gov/sites/default/files/STEM%20Best%20Awardees%20Press%20Release%2010.24.19.pdf

post_text: The Middle School "Pay It Forward" book club is joining the World Kindness Movement on November 13. We are planning to spread kindness to those in the BCLUW area that are currently serving in the military. If you would like to help, we are collecting donations for care package items such as snack bars, gum, powdered drink sticks, magazines, crossword puzzles, and sunflower seeds. The Middle School students will be assembling the packages on November 13. Stop by our table during conferences and we'll update you on our kindness project! Thank you!

shared_text:
North Central District FFA
September 30, 2019 at 9:31 PM ·

This week’s Member Monday is Abby Feldpausch from the BCLUW FFA Chapter! Abby is a senior at BCLUW and has served as the chapter’s president for two years, as well as the chapter’s secretary and as a NC District Reporter. Abby has been very involved in the FFA throughout her years of high school by participating in the Creed Speaking, Ag Broadcasting, Livestock Judging, Poultry Judging, and Public Speaking development events. She has attended National Convention twice, participated in Meals From the Heartland, and has shown livestock at the county and state fair. Abby is a very active member within our district and was nominated because of this! 💛💙
